                <![CDATA[
                    🧠 The Stress-Motor Pathway (Amygdalo-Striato-PPT) This pathway describes the neuroanatomical and biochemical sequence from sensory threat detection to motor system potentiation, via cortisol-driven glutamatergic upregulation in the striatum. It links emotional stress, habit biasing, and motor readiness, and plays a central role in disorders like&hellip;
                ]]>
            </summary>
        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                <p data-start="601" data-end="655"><strong data-start="601" data-end="655">🧠 The Stress-Motor Pathway (Amygdalo-Striato-PPT)</strong></p>
<p data-start="657" data-end="1049">This pathway describes the neuroanatomical and biochemical sequence from <strong data-start="730" data-end="758">sensory threat detection</strong> to <strong data-start="762" data-end="791">motor system potentiation</strong>, via cortisol-driven glutamatergic upregulation in the striatum. It links <strong data-start="866" data-end="886">emotional stress</strong>, <strong data-start="888" data-end="905">habit biasing</strong>, and <strong data-start="911" data-end="930">motor readiness</strong>, and plays a central role in disorders like <strong data-start="975" data-end="982">ALS</strong>, <strong data-start="984" data-end="1021">REM Sleep Behavior Disorder (RBD)</strong>, and <strong data-start="1027" data-end="1048">Fibromyalgia (FM)</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="1051" data-end="1054">
<h3 data-start="1056" data-end="1098">1. Sensory Input → Thalamus → Amygdala</h3>
<p data-start="1100" data-end="1146">External stimuli are relayed via the thalamus:</p>
<ul data-start="1147" data-end="1258">
<li data-start="1147" data-end="1175">
<p data-start="1149" data-end="1175"><strong data-start="1149" data-end="1156">LGN</strong> for visual input</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1176" data-end="1206">
<p data-start="1178" data-end="1206"><strong data-start="1178" data-end="1185">MGN</strong> for auditory input</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1207" data-end="1258">
<p data-start="1209" data-end="1258"><strong data-start="1209" data-end="1232">Ventrobasal complex</strong> for somatosensory input</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1260" data-end="1320">These project rapidly to the <strong data-start="1289" data-end="1319">Basolateral Amygdala (BLA)</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="1322" data-end="1340"><strong data-start="1322" data-end="1340">Cited Sources:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="1341" data-end="1760">
<li data-start="1341" data-end="1550">
<p data-start="1343" data-end="1550">"In the amygdala, the BLA is in receipt of early multimodal sensory information from the thalamus and cortex..."<br data-start="1455" data-end="1458"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30186100/" data-start="1458" data-end="1499"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30186100/</a><br data-start="1499" data-end="1502">7_Visceral_Stress_Modulation_Amygdala_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1552" data-end="1760">
<p data-start="1554" data-end="1760">"Chronic stress significantly altered the morphology and synaptic physiology of amygdala projection neurons..."<br data-start="1665" data-end="1668"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30060908/" data-start="1668" data-end="1709"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30060908/</a><br data-start="1709" data-end="1712">7_Visceral_Stress_Modulation_Amygdala_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1762" data-end="1765">
<h3 data-start="1767" data-end="1854">2. Amygdala → Hypothalamus → HPA Axis Activation → Cortisol Priming of the Striatum</h3>
<p data-start="1856" data-end="1948">The <strong data-start="1860" data-end="1886">Central Amygdala (CeA)</strong> indirectly activates the <strong data-start="1912" data-end="1919">PVN</strong> via a disinhibition circuit:</p>
<ul data-start="1949" data-end="2056">
<li data-start="1949" data-end="1990">
<p data-start="1951" data-end="1990">CeA inhibits BST (both are GABAergic)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1991" data-end="2056">
<p data-start="1993" data-end="2056">This disinhibits the PVN, initiating the stress hormone cascade</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2058" data-end="2184">The PVN releases <strong data-start="2075" data-end="2082">CRH</strong>, which prompts the pituitary to secrete <strong data-start="2123" data-end="2131">ACTH</strong>, causing the adrenal cortex to release <strong data-start="2171" data-end="2183">cortisol</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="2186" data-end="2203"><strong data-start="2186" data-end="2203">Cited Source:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="2204" data-end="2464">
<li data-start="2204" data-end="2367">
<p data-start="2206" data-end="2367">"The CeA–BST–PVN circuit may utilize two GABA synapses..."<br data-start="2264" data-end="2267"><a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0091302203000293" data-start="2267" data-end="2338"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0091302203000293</a><br data-start="2338" data-end="2341">1_Stress_to_ALS_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2369" data-end="2464">
<p data-start="2371" data-end="2464">"Lesions of the CeA cause depletion of CRH..."<br data-start="2417" data-end="2420">Same link above<br data-start="2435" data-end="2438">1_Stress_to_ALS_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="2466" data-end="2469">
<h3 data-start="2471" data-end="2532">3. Cortisol → Striatal Modulation (Dorsolateral Striatum)</h3>
<p data-start="2534" data-end="2626">Cortisol binds to <strong data-start="2552" data-end="2586">glucocorticoid receptors (GRs)</strong> in the <strong data-start="2594" data-end="2625">Dorsolateral Striatum (DLS)</strong>.</p>
<ul data-start="2628" data-end="2794">
<li data-start="2628" data-end="2678">
<p data-start="2630" data-end="2678"><strong data-start="2630" data-end="2641">D1-MSNs</strong> become more excitable to glutamate</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2679" data-end="2729">
<p data-start="2681" data-end="2729">Inhibition by <strong data-start="2695" data-end="2716">SOM+ interneurons</strong> is reduced</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2730" data-end="2794">
<p data-start="2732" data-end="2794">Net result: increased output, increased risk of excitotoxicity</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2796" data-end="2814"><strong data-start="2796" data-end="2814">Cited Sources:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="2815" data-end="3130">
<li data-start="2815" data-end="2958">
<p data-start="2817" data-end="2958">"Chronic exposure to stress leads to overactivation..."<br data-start="2872" data-end="2875"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36446783/" data-start="2875" data-end="2916"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36446783/</a><br data-start="2916" data-end="2919">2_Circuitry_and_Neuroanatomy_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2960" data-end="3130">
<p data-start="2962" data-end="3130">"Corticosterone has a selective neuroendangering action within the striatum."<br data-start="3039" data-end="3042"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15946160/" data-start="3042" data-end="3083"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15946160/</a><br data-start="3083" data-end="3086">3_Sex_Differences_and_Nociception_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="3132" data-end="3135">
<h3 data-start="3137" data-end="3195">4. Striatum → Basal Ganglia Output → PPT Disinhibition</h3>
<p data-start="3197" data-end="3229"><strong data-start="3197" data-end="3208">D1-MSNs</strong> project directly to:</p>
<ul data-start="3230" data-end="3249">
<li data-start="3230" data-end="3239">
<p data-start="3232" data-end="3239"><strong data-start="3232" data-end="3239">SNr</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3240" data-end="3249">
<p data-start="3242" data-end="3249"><strong data-start="3242" data-end="3249">GPi</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3251" data-end="3353">This reduces basal ganglia inhibition, disinhibiting the <strong data-start="3308" data-end="3352">Pedunculopontine Tegmental Nucleus (PPT)</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="3355" data-end="3373"><strong data-start="3355" data-end="3373">Cited Sources:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="3374" data-end="3654">
<li data-start="3374" data-end="3522">
<p data-start="3376" data-end="3522">"Striatal neurons... projecting to MGP and SNr..."<br data-start="3426" data-end="3429"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8732541/" data-start="3429" data-end="3469"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8732541/</a><br data-start="3469" data-end="3472">4_Glutamate_Excitotoxicity_and_Lifespan_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3524" data-end="3654">
<p data-start="3526" data-end="3654">"Efferents from the SNr and GPi... modulate REM atonia."<br data-start="3582" data-end="3585"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9406329/" data-start="3585" data-end="3625"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9406329/</a><br data-start="3625" data-end="3628">1_Stress_to_ALS_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="3656" data-end="3659">
<h3 data-start="3661" data-end="3709">5. PPT → Reticulospinal Tract → Motor System</h3>
<p data-start="3711" data-end="3764">PPT activates <strong data-start="3725" data-end="3751">reticulospinal neurons</strong>, leading to:</p>
<ul data-start="3765" data-end="3861">
<li data-start="3765" data-end="3790">
<p data-start="3767" data-end="3790">Increased muscle tone</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3791" data-end="3828">
<p data-start="3793" data-end="3828">Increased postural reflexes (PPA)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3829" data-end="3861">
<p data-start="3831" data-end="3861">Increased startle reactivity</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3863" data-end="3881"><strong data-start="3863" data-end="3881">Cited Sources:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="3882" data-end="4286">
<li data-start="3882" data-end="4017">
<p data-start="3884" data-end="4017">"rPPN-vGluT2 neurons project to... spinal cord"<br data-start="3931" data-end="3934"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39527367/" data-start="3934" data-end="3975"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39527367/</a><br data-start="3975" data-end="3978">2_Circuitry_and_Neuroanatomy_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4019" data-end="4147">
<p data-start="4021" data-end="4147">"PPN to spinal cord projections exist..."<br data-start="4062" data-end="4065"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2129877/" data-start="4065" data-end="4105"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2129877/</a><br data-start="4105" data-end="4108">2_Circuitry_and_Neuroanatomy_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4149" data-end="4286">
<p data-start="4151" data-end="4286">"Selective targeting of glutamatergic neurons..."<br data-start="4200" data-end="4203"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35082287/" data-start="4203" data-end="4244"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35082287/</a><br data-start="4244" data-end="4247">2_Circuitry_and_Neuroanatomy_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4288" data-end="4291">
<h3 data-start="4293" data-end="4337">6. Chronic Activation → Excitotoxic Risk</h3>
<p data-start="4339" data-end="4416">Chronic activation leads to glutamate overload and motor neuron degeneration.</p>
<p data-start="4418" data-end="4436"><strong data-start="4418" data-end="4436">Cited Sources:</strong></p>
<ul data-start="4437" data-end="4776">
<li data-start="4437" data-end="4637">
<p data-start="4439" data-end="4637">"Increased glutamatergic signaling causes motor neurons to become hyperexcitable and eventually die."<br data-start="4540" data-end="4543"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38891774/" data-start="4543" data-end="4584"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38891774/</a><br data-start="4584" data-end="4587">4_Glutamate_Excitotoxicity_and_Lifespan_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4639" data-end="4776">
<p data-start="4641" data-end="4776">"Chronic stress causes striatal disinhibition..."<br data-start="4690" data-end="4693"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36446783/" data-start="4693" data-end="4734"  target="_new"  class=" extlink extlink-icon-1"  rel="noopener noreferrer">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36446783/</a><br data-start="4734" data-end="4737">2_Circuitry_and_Neuroanatomy_Master.pdf</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4778" data-end="4781">
